# This is straight Nihon-shiki and Kunrei-shiki Roomaji.
# The presumption is that if one is typing Hiragana one is not writing Internet slang or loanwords, or expecting non-kana symbols, or transliterating.
# One is writing actual Japanese words, and the ASCII is basically a 2-letter or 3-letter array reference to the kana.
#
# "little" kana are spelled with an initial "l", so "little a" is "la"; this matches Microsoft input methods.
# Open Chinese Desktop uses "_" instead.
# An initial "x" is not used.
#
# For spelling "little tu" directly "ltu" is available.
# "little tu" is also, and mainly, spelled by gemination, so "ppo" spells the two kana っぽ ("little tu" + "po").
#
# Spellings are not case sensitive.
# This does not need to distinguish hiragana from katakana with ASCII case; as katakana is a separate input method and thereby already distinguished.
# The keyboard engravings make it look lower case, though; to preserve the feeling of the old lower-case-means-hiragana convention.
#
%ename Hiragana
%jname ひらがな
%cname 日文平假
%selkey 1234567890
%keyname begin
a a
b b
c c
d d
e e
f f
g g
h h
i i
j j
k k
l l
m m
n n
o o
p p
q q
r r
s s
t t
u u
v v
w w
x x
y y
z z
- -
%keyname end
